<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Currently, we do not have access to the type specimens.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
We have examined several specimens from Malaysia and India that are very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="Longtitarsella" lsidName="Longtitarsella notatipennis" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="notatipennis">Longtitarsella notatipennis</taxonomicName>
, except for the shape of the aedeagus, which is slightly different from the description provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Medvedev, LN" journalOrPublisher="KMK Scientific Press, Moscow" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" title="Alticinae of Indochina." year="2009">Medvedev (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. The aedeagus is gradually widened from base to rounded apex in the specimens at our disposal, however, according to the original description and illustration provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Medvedev, LN" journalOrPublisher="KMK Scientific Press, Moscow" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" title="Alticinae of Indochina." year="2009">Medvedev (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, the aedeagus is gradually narrowed from base to rounded apex. Hence the types should be examined to ensure identity of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
